  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my friends and neighbors in Bari. As a carpenter with no formal education beyond high school, I know how important practical skills are, but I've also noticed how students from backgrounds where STEM isn't emphasized can feel intimidated when they're in classrooms or workshops where everyone seems to know the 'right' way to do things. For example, my nephew, who's smart but never really got into math, started to doubt himself after a school project where he was told 'you're not good at this.' That's stereotype threat in action—it's the fear that your group's stereotypes might hurt your performance. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big, sweeping policies that don't consider real-world constraints. In Bari, where many families struggle with the cost of education, we need to focus on small, practical steps: maybe workshops for parents to understand how to support their kids without overwhelming them, or simple mentorship programs that pair students with local tradespeople like me who can show them that STEM isn't just about books and exams—it's about solving real problems, like building a house or fixing a broken machine. I've been depressed lately, and it's hard to see how these issues can be fixed when people feel so disconnected from the system. But I believe that if we can create spaces where kids feel safe to make mistakes and learn from them, we can help reduce the stigma around STEM. It's not about changing the system overnight—it's about building bridges, one conversation at a time.",
